Working with categorical predictors

Matthew Rudd

3/3/2022

The primary message in the first example is:

Categorical data is not quantitative!

Logistic regression: violet data

Load the violet data and compute the bud formation rates for each plot:

library(tidyverse)
violets <- read_csv("violets.csv")
violets <- violets %>%
  mutate(Bud = as.numeric( `Bud counts` > 0 ))

(violet_plots <- violets %>%
  group_by(Plot) %>% 
  summarize( N = n(),
             Rate = mean(Bud)) )
## # A tibble: 10  3
##     Plot     N  Rate
##    <dbl> <int> <dbl>
##  1     1    32 0.25 
##  2     2    32 0.5  
##  3     3    32 0.438
##  4     4    32 0.438
##  5     5    32 0.469
##  6     6    32 0.5  
##  7     7    32 0.469
##  8     8    32 0.5  
##  9     9    32 0.469
## 10    10    32 0.469

The different plots are numbered 1 through 10; by default, R therefore considers Plot to be a numeric variable, which we can confirm by checking its type:

class(violets$Plot)
## [1] "numeric"

What could go wrong?

Useless model when Plot is numeric

If we fit a logistic model now, using Plot as a quantitative variable, the results are terrible:

violet.fit <- glm( Bud ~ Plot, data=violets, family="binomial")
summary( violet.fit )
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = Bud ~ Plot, family = "binomial", data = violets)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.1945  -1.1041  -0.9957   1.2526   1.3707  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)  
## (Intercept) -0.49752    0.24545  -2.027   0.0427 *
## Plot         0.05376    0.03933   1.367   0.1717  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 440.41  on 319  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 438.53  on 318  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 442.53
##

violet_plots <- violet_plots %>%
  mutate( Fit = predict( violet.fit, 
                         newdata = data.frame(Plot = 1:10),
                         type = "response"))

violet_plots
## # A tibble: 10  4
##     Plot     N  Rate   Fit

##  1     1    32 0.25  0.391

##  9     9    32 0.469 0.497
## 10    10    32 0.469 0.510

The fitted values, which should correspond to the probabilities of bud formation in each plot, are not good estimates of the empirical rates.

Reasonable model when Plot is categorical

Once we recognize that Plot is categorical and convert it into a factor, the resulting logistic model works well:

violets$Plot <- as.factor( violets$Plot )
violet.fit <- glm( Bud ~ Plot, data=violets, family="binomial")
summary( violet.fit )
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = Bud ~ Plot, family = "binomial", data = violets)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.1774  -1.1247  -0.7585   1.2310   1.6651  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)   
## (Intercept)  -1.0986     0.4082  -2.691  0.00712 **
## Plot2         1.0986     0.5401   2.034  0.04193 * 
## Plot3         0.8473     0.5419   1.564  0.11792   
## Plot4         0.8473     0.5419   1.564  0.11792   
## Plot5         0.9734     0.5405   1.801  0.07171 . 
## Plot6         1.0986     0.5401   2.034  0.04193 * 
## Plot7         0.9734     0.5405   1.801  0.07171 . 
## Plot8         1.0986     0.5401   2.034  0.04193 * 
## Plot9         0.9734     0.5405   1.801  0.07171 . 
## Plot10        0.9734     0.5405   1.801  0.07171 .

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

violet_plots <- violet_plots %>%
  mutate( Fit = predict( violet.fit, 
                         newdata = data.frame(Plot = levels(violets$Plot)),
                         type = "response"))

violet_plots
## # A tibble: 10  4
##     Plot     N  Rate   Fit
##    <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl>
##  1     1    32 0.25  0.250
##  2     2    32 0.5   0.500
##  3     3    32 0.438 0.437
##  4     4    32 0.438 0.437
##  5     5    32 0.469 0.469
##  6     6    32 0.5   0.500
##  7     7    32 0.469 0.469
##  8     8    32 0.5   0.500
##  9     9    32 0.469 0.469
## 10    10    32 0.469 0.469

This is what happens when working with one categorical predictor:

the model predictions are the group averages.

In this case, the average for a group (a plot) is the empirical probability of bud formation, i.e., the percentage of days on which new buds were observed in a given plot.

Linear regression: infant mortality rates by continent

Visualize the data and examine the summary stats

imr <- read_csv("imr2011.csv")
## Rows: 195 Columns: 3
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (2): Country, Continent
## dbl (1): IMR
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
imr$Continent <- as.factor(imr$Continent)
imr <- imr %>%
  mutate( Continent = fct_reorder(Continent, -IMR))

ggplot( imr, aes( x=IMR, y=Continent, color=Continent)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_point() +
  theme( legend.position = "none")

imr_means <- imr %>% 
  group_by(Continent) %>%
  summarize( Mean = mean(IMR)) 

imr_means %>%
  arrange(Mean)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   Continent      Mean
##   <fct>         <dbl>
## 1 Europe         4.98
## 2 North America 15.7 
## 3 South America 18.2 
## 4 Oceania       19.8 
## 5 Asia          24.1 
## 6 Africa        60.1

Linear regression model

imr.fit <- lm( IMR ~ Continent, data = imr )
summary(imr.fit)

Linear regression with 2 predictors

heights <- read_csv("all_heights.csv")
## Rows: 2453 Columns: 3
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): Sex
## dbl (2): Parent, Child
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
ggplot( heights, aes(x=Parent, y=Child, color=Sex)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot( heights, aes(x=Parent, y=Child, color=Sex)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth( method="lm", level=0)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

# no interaction
heights.fit <- lm( Child ~ Parent + Sex, data=heights)
summary(heights.fit)
